\headerbox{Ciguatera fish poisoning}{name=ciguatera,column=1,row=0}{
\textbf{Severity:} Ciguatera is a highly morbid, potentially fatal disease.\\
\textbf{Transmission:} Through bioaccumulation toxins are consumed with \emph{Gambierdiscus} spp. and  then transferred through food chain via predation.\\
\textbf{High risk area:} Pacific Island Nations, for example life time incidence in New Caledonia are 35-70\%.\\
\textbf{Symptomatology:} 180+ gastrointestinal, cardiovascular and neurological symptoms \cite{bagnis}.
}

\headerbox{Genetics}{name=genetics,span=2,column=1,row=0,below=ciguatera}{
\textbf{Methods:} Genomic DNA extracted (CTAB); amplification of large sub-unit (LSU) ribosomal DNA (rDNA) and the small-sub unit (SSU) rDNA regions via PCR then Sanger sequenced by Macrogen (Korea). Results aligned with sequences from GenBank. Phylogenetics inferences calculated with Bayesian inference as well as maximum likelihood. \\
\textbf{Results:} \emph{G. lapillus} forms a genetically distinct, well supported clade (Fig. 2).
\begin{center}
	\includegraphics[width=0.85\linewidth]{phylo-sml-trans.png}
	\end{center}
	Fig. 2: Phylogenetic analysis of \emph{G. lapillus}.  Maximum likelihood phylogeny of \emph{Gambierdiscus} spp. and phylotypes. Nodal support are Bayesian posterior probability (PP) and bootstraps (BS). Strong support (PP/BT = 1.00/100) shown as thick line. (A) SSU region 1699 bp; (B) D8-D10 LSU region  799 bp.
}

\headerbox{Size}{name=size,span=2,column=1,row=0,below=genetics}{
\begin{minipage}[b]{0.53\linewidth}
\textbf{Methods:} Strains HG4, HG6 HG7 and HG26 were fixed in 10\% Lugol's iodide during exponential growth phase and examined with inverted light microscope (Nikon Eclipse TS100, Infinite Luminera 1 camera). Depth (along dorso-ventral axis) and width (along lateral axis) (n=128).\\
\textbf{Results:} \emph{G. lapillus} is consistently much smaller than any other \emph{Gambierdiscus} spp, comparable with the sister genus \emph{Fukuyoa}.
\end{minipage}
\hfill
\begin{minipage}[b]{0.43\linewidth}
\includegraphics[width=0.98\linewidth]{graph-trans.png}
Fig. 3: Size difference \emph{Gambierdiscus} spp. Error bars denote standard deviation.
\end{minipage}
}


\headerbox{Conclusion}{name=conc,span=2,column=1,row=0,below=size}{
The evidence for \emph{Gambierdiscus lapillus} sp. nov. is based on unique genetic regions to other \emph{Gambierdiscus} spp. (Fig. 2), supported by morphology (Fig. 1) and consistently diminutive size (Fig. 3). The species is named for the latter along with heavy plate ornamentation characteristic of it's members. Latin, lapillus (= little gem).
This constitutes the 4th \emph{Gambierdiscus} spp. identified around Australia, however none are verified ciguatoxin producers by LC-MS/MS. Hence the causative organism of ciguatera fish poisoning in Australia is still unknown. This makes the investigation into the uncharacterised peaks in the ciguatoxin transition a priority for future work.
}

